# Merge Sorted Array

## Difficulty
Easy

## Approach
Use three pointers starting from the end of the arrays.

- `m - 1` points to the last valid element in `nums1`.
- `n - 1` points to the last element in `nums2`.
- `last` points to the last position in `nums1`.

Compare the elements from the end of both arrays and place the larger one at `nums1[last]`. Move the corresponding pointer backward and continue until one of the arrays is exhausted.

If elements remain in `nums2`, copy them into the front of `nums1`. Any remaining elements in `nums1` are already in their correct positions.

## Complexity
- **Time Complexity:** O(m + n)
- **Space Complexity:** O(1)

## Code
```python
class Solution:
    def merge(self, nums1, m, nums2, n):
        last = m + n - 1

        while m > 0 and n > 0:
            if nums1[m - 1] > nums2[n - 1]:
                nums1[last] = nums1[m - 1]
                m -= 1
            else:
                nums1[last] = nums2[n - 1]
                n -= 1

            last -= 1

        while n > 0:
            nums1[last] = nums2[n - 1]
            n -= 1
            last -= 1
```
